# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asme-y14-41
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Its use in designing electronic systems is known as *electronic design automation* (*EDA*).
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] In mechanical design it is known as *mechanical design automation* (*MDA*), which includes the process of creating a technical drawing with the use of computer software.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD software for mechanical design uses either vector-based graphics to depict the objects of traditional drafting, or may also produce raster graphics showing the overall appearance of designed objects.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] However, it involves more than just shapes.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] As in the manual drafting of technical and engineering drawings, the output of CAD must convey information, such as materials, processes, dimensions, and tolerances, according to application-specific conventions.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD may be used to design curves and figures in two-dimensional (2D) space; or curves, surfaces, and solids in three-dimensional (3D) space.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD is an important industrial art extensively used in many applications, including automotive, shipbuilding, and aerospace industries, industrial and architectural design (building information modeling), prosthetics, and many more.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD is also widely used to produce computer animation for special effects in movies, advertising and technical manuals, often called DCC digital content creation.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] The modern ubiquity and power of computers means that even perfume bottles and shampoo dispensers are designed using techniques unheard of by engineers of the 1960s.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Because of its enormous economic importance, CAD has been a major driving force for research in computational geometry, computer graphics (both hardware and software), and discrete differential geometry.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] The design of geometric models for object shapes, in particular, is occasionally called **computer-aided geometric design** (**CAGD**).
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Computer-aided design is one of the many tools used by engineers and designers and is used in many ways depending on the profession of the user and the type of software in question.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Potential blockage of view corridors and shadow studies are also frequently analyzed through the use of CAD.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] There are several different types of CAD, each requiring the operator to think differently about how to use them and design their virtual components in a different manner.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Virtually all of CAD tools rely on constraint concepts that are used to define geometric or non-geometric elements of a model.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] There are many producers of the lower-end 2D sketching systems, including a number of free and open-source programs.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] These provide an approach to the drawing process where scale and placement on the drawing sheet can easily be adjusted in the final draft as required, unlike in hand drafting.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Top-end CAD systems offer the capability to incorporate more organic, aesthetic and ergonomic features into the designs.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Freeform surface modeling is often combined with solids to allow the designer to create products that fit the human form and visual requirements as well as they interface with the machine.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Today, CAD systems exist for all the major platforms (Windows, Linux, UNIX and Mac OS X); some packages support multiple platforms.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Starting with the IBM Drafting System in the mid-1960s, computer-aided design systems began to provide more capabilities than just an ability to reproduce manual drafting with electronic drafting, and the cost-benefit for companies to switch to CAD became apparent.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] The software automated many tasks that are taken for granted from computer systems today, such as automated generation of bills of materials, auto layout in integrated circuits, interference checking, and many others.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Eventually, CAD provided the designer with the ability to perform engineering calculations.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] During this transition, calculations were still performed either by hand or by those individuals who could run computer programs.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD was a revolutionary change in the engineering industry, where draftsman, designer, and engineer roles that had previously been separate began to merge.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD is an example of the pervasive effect computers were beginning to have on the industry.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Current computer-aided design software packages range from 2D vector-based drafting systems to 3D solid and surface modelers.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Modern CAD packages can also frequently allow rotations in three dimensions, allowing viewing of a designed object from any desired angle, even from the inside looking out.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Some CAD software is capable of dynamic mathematical modeling.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD technology is used in the design of tools and machinery and in the drafting and design of all types of buildings, from small residential types (houses) to the largest commercial and industrial structures (hospitals and factories).
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD is mainly used for detailed design of 3D models or 2D drawings of physical components, but it is also used throughout the engineering process from conceptual design and layout of products, through strength and dynamic analysis of assemblies to definition of manufacturing methods of components.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] It can also be used to design objects such as jewelry, furniture, appliances, etc.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Furthermore, many CAD applications now offer advanced rendering and animation capabilities so engineers can better visualize their product designs.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] 4D BIM is a type of virtual construction engineering simulation incorporating time or schedule-related information for project management.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD has become an especially important technology within the scope of computer-aided technologies, with benefits such as lower product development costs and a greatly shortened design cycle.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD enables designers to layout and develop work on screen, print it out and save it for future editing, saving time on their drawings.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] In the 2000s, some CAD system software vendors shipped their distributions with a dedicated license manager software that controlled how often or how many users can utilize the CAD system.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] It could run either on a local machine (by loading from a local storage device) or a local network fileserver and was usually tied to a specific IP address in latter case.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] CAD software enables engineers and architects to design, inspect and manage engineering projects within an integrated graphical user interface (GUI) on a personal computer system.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Most applications support solid modeling with boundary representation (B-Rep) and NURBS geometry, and enable the same to be published in a variety of formats.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] Based on market statistics, commercial software from Autodesk, Dassault Systèmes, Siemens PLM Software, and PTC dominate the CAD industry.
[src:asme-y14-41/3d-computer-aided-design] The following is a list of major CAD applications, grouped by usage statistics.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] As a Standards Development Organization, ASME continues to develop and maintains nearly 600 codes and standards in a wide range of disciplines including pressure technology, nuclear plants, elevators / escalators, construction, engineering design, and performance testing.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Machine Tool standards are developed and maintained by ASME B5 Committee, which operates under ASME's Board on Standardization and Testing.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee currently meets once a year in various locations throughout the United States.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The meeting is generally held in November and is open to the public.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The B5 Technical Committees usually meet in conjunction with the B5 Standards Committee.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Some B5 Technical Committees also meet separately in different locations throughout the year.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee and its Technical Committees are composed of experts in the field of machine tools.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Members of the B5 Standards Committee are classified in the following interest classes: Producer/Manufacturer, Regulatory, Services, General Interest, and User.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The B5 Committee works on writing new ASME American National Standards, and revising current ASME B5 and B94 standards.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee operates under procedures of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The celebration of the 100th meeting in 2022 will mark the 100th consecutive year the ASME B5 committee has met.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The following historical information marks only the beginning stages of copious collaborative work and continuous publication, review, and revision of ASME B5 Standards.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] On May 13, 1914, the ASME Committee on Meetings, Subcommittee on Machine Shop Practice began discussion on standardization of machine shop practices.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] It wasn't until September 1922 under the procedure of American Standards Association, the B5 committee was organized as a committee dedicated to machine tools.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] B5 was sponsored by the National Machine Tool Builders’ Association, the Society of Automotive Engineers, Metal Cutting Tool Institute, and The American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] On December 2, 1937, the standard for Adjustable Adapters for Multiple Spindle Drilling Heads this standard was approved by the American Standards Association and designated as American Standard (ASA B5.11-1937).
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Work on the standardization of T-slots started in 1924 and a tentative standard was published in 1927.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The first official American Standard for T-slots came in 1941.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] 11 was organized in New York on December 4, 1928, and B5 Technical Committee No.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] 4 on Spindle Noses was organized on December 5, 1928.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] These two committees worked in close cooperation with each other and with manufacturers and users of engine lathes, turret lathes and automatic lathes in developing standards for spindle noses and chucks.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] 3 on the Standardization of Machine Tapers was appointed in August, 1926, and held its organization meeting in September, 1926, in New Haven, Conn.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Three American tapers then in use, the Brown & Sharpe (1860), Morse (1862), and Jarno (1889), and the taper series adopted by William Sellers & Co.(1862) were combined into a compromise standard series which contained twenty-two (22) self-holding taper sizes.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The first edition of the Spindle Noses and Tool Shanks for Milling Machines standard, known as B5.18-1943, resulted from intensive effort dating back to 1926 by a special group of milling machine manufacturers.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] The effort to establish an American standard for Ball Screws began in July 1971 out of a need to obtain a consensus opinion relative to proposals for standardization of ball screw assemblies within the ISO/TC39 sub-committee Working Group 7.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Out of this, the subcommittee TC43 was organized with members representing manufacturers, users of ball screws, and others of general interest.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] TC43 produced ANSI B5.48, which was approved as an American National Standard and published in 1977.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Technical subcommittees under ASME B5 address the formulation and maintenance of standards in particular disciplines within the scope of the B5 charter.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Membership includes a carefully balanced representation in various interest classifications so that no one group dominates.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Some examples of the various interest classifications are: users, manufacturers, consultants, insurance interests, universities, testing laboratories, and government regulatory agencies.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] There are over 40 Standards that are periodically reviewed to ensure they reflect new developments and technical advances (e.g., new materials, new designs and new applications).
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-b5] Several new standards are under development or being considered in the areas of Tool Holder Interfaces, Machine Performance Evaluation, Micromachining, Energy Assessment, and Robotics.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The **ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC)** is a set of standards published by the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) that provides rules for the design, fabrication, inspection, testing, and certification of boilers and pressure vessels.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The BPVC is developed and updated through a consensus process managed by ASME committees, with participation from volunteer technical experts representing industry, regulators, and other stakeholders.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] ASME also operates a conformity assessment and certification system under which accredited organizations—including manufacturers and authorized inspection agencies—may apply ASME Code Symbol Stamps to equipment that meets BPVC requirements.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The BPVC was created in response to public outcry after several serious explosions in the state of Massachusetts.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] A fire-tube boiler exploded at the Grover Shoe Factory in Brockton, Massachusetts, on March 20, 1905, which resulted in the deaths of 58 people and injured 150.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Then on December 6, 1906, a boiler in the factory of the P.J.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Harney Shoe Company exploded in Lynn, Massachusetts.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] As a result, the state of Massachusetts enacted the first legal code based on ASME's rules for the construction of steam boilers in 1907.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] ASME convened the Board of Boiler Rules before it became the ASME Boiler Code Committee which was formed in 1911.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This committee put in the form work for the first edition of the ASME Boiler Code - Rules for the Construction of Stationary Boilers and for the Allowable Working Pressures, which was issued in 1914 and published in 1915.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The first edition of the Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code, known as the 1914 edition, was a single 114-page volume.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It developed over time into the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel code, which today has over 92,000 copies in use, in over 100 countries around the world.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] As of March 2011 the document consisted of 16,000 pages in 28 volumes.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] After the first edition of the Code, the verifications required by the Code were performed by independent inspectors, which resulted in a wide range of interpretations.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Hence in February 1919, the National Board of Boiler and Pressure Vessel Inspectors was formed.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Addenda, which include additions and revisions to the individual Sections of the Code, are issued accordingly for a particular edition of the code up until the next edition.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Addenda is no longer in use since Code Edition 2013.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It has been replaced by two years edition period.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] ASME's interpretations to submitted technical queries relevant to a particular Section of the Code are issued accordingly.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Interpretations are also available through the internet.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Code Cases provide rules that permit the use of materials and alternative methods of construction that are not covered by existing BPVC rules.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Codes Cases are usually intended to be incorporated in the Code in a later edition.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] When it is used, the Code Case specifies mandatory requirements which must be met as it would be with the Code.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] There are some jurisdictions that do not automatically accept Code Cases.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The section of the ASME BPVC consists of 4 parts.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This Part is a supplementary book referenced by other sections of the Code.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It provides material specifications for ferrous materials which are suitable for use in the construction of pressure vessels.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The specifications contained in this Part specify the mechanical properties, heat treatment, heat and product chemical composition and analysis, test specimens, and methodologies of testing.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The designation of the specifications start with 'SA' and a number which is taken from the ASTM 'A' specifications.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It provides material specifications for nonferrous materials which are suitable for use in the construction of pressure vessels.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The designation of the specifications start with 'SB' and a number which is taken from the ASTM 'B' specifications.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It provides mechanical properties, heat treatment, heat and product chemical composition and analysis, test specimens, and methodologies of testing for welding rods, filler metals and electrodes used in the construction of pressure vessels.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The specifications contained in this Part are designated with 'SFA' and a number which is taken from the American Welding Society (AWS) specifications.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section III of the ASME Code Address the rules for construction of nuclear facility components and supports.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The components and supports covered by section III are intended to be installed in a nuclear power system that serves the purpose of producing and controlling the output of thermal energy from nuclear fuel and those associated systems essential to safety of nuclear power system.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section III provides requirements for new construction of nuclear power system considering mechanical and thermal stresses due to cyclic operation.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Deterioration, which may occur in service as result of radiation effects, corrosion, or instability of the material, is typically not addressed.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This section of the ASME BPVC contains the requirements for nondestructive examinations which are referred and required by other sections of the Code.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It also covers the suppliers examination responsibilities, requirements of the authorized inspectors (AI) as well as the requirements for the qualification of personnel, inspection and examinations.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This section of the ASME BPVC consists of 3 divisions.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] 1 covers the mandatory requirements, specific prohibitions and nonmandatory guidance for materials, design, fabrication, inspection and testing, markings and reports, overpressure protection and certification of pressure vessels having an internal or external pressure which exceeds 15 psi (100 kPa).
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Pressure vessels covered by this division can be either fired or unfired.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure may be from external sources, or by the application of heating from an indirect or direct source, or any combination thereof.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The division is not numbered in the traditional method (Part 1, Part 2 etc.) but is structured with Subsections and Parts which consist of letters followed by a number.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure vessels can be either fired or unfired.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure may be from external sources, or by the application of heating from an indirect or direct source as a result of a process, or any combination of the two.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The rules contained in this section can be used as an alternative to the minimum requirements specified in Division 1.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Generally the Division 2 rules are more onerous than in Division 1 with respect to materials, design and nondestructive examinations but higher design stress intensity values are allowed.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Division 2 has also provisions for the use of finite element analysis to determine expected stress in pressure equipment, in addition to the traditional approach of *design by formula* (Part 5: "Design by Analysis requirements").
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure vessel can be either fired or unfired.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure may be from external sources, by the application of heating from an indirect or direct source, process reaction or any combination thereof.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Prior to the introduction of Section IX, individual sections of the BPVC contained their own separate and varying qualification requirements for welded construction.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section IX was first published as a standalone section of the BPVC in 1941, initially covering only three welding processes: Shielded Metal Arc Welding (SMAW), Oxy-Fuel Welding (OFW), and Carbon-Arc Welding (CAW).
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The fundamental philosophy of qualifying procedures and personnel while permitting qualified ranges of variables has remained largely unchanged since this first edition.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Although additional joining processes and qualification rules have been incorporated over time to keep pace with industrial technology, the core mechanics of the code have remained highly stable.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The scope of Section IX has expanded periodically over its history.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Brazing qualifications were incorporated in the 1960 edition, turning it into the "Welding and Brazing Qualifications" standard.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The 2013 edition introduced qualification requirements for plastic fusing, along with a common set of general requirements applicable to all material-joining processes.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] For welding, Section IX establishes requirements for qualifying Welding Procedure Specifications (WPSs) by means of Procedure Qualification Records (PQRs) and for qualifying welders and welding operators through performance qualification tests.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Similar qualification systems are provided for brazing procedures and brazers, and for plastic fusing procedures and operators.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] To reduce the administrative and economic burden of procedure qualifications, Section IX groups base materials into P-Numbers and welding filler metals into F-Numbers.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Qualification of a procedure using one material or filler metal may therefore extend to other materials or filler metals within the same classification, subject to the qualification rules of the Code.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section IX is referenced by numerous ASME construction codes, including those governing boilers, pressure vessels, and pressure piping.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Because of its rigorous framework and historical reliability, it is widely used internationally as the definitive qualification standard for joining procedures and personnel in pressure equipment fabrication, even in countries that do not otherwise utilize the ASME construction codes.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Within ISO-based manufacturing systems, it serves a functionally parallel purpose to the ISO 15614 series (for procedure qualification) and the ISO 9606 series (for personnel qualification).
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] New editions of the standard are generally approved and published every two years.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] The ASME Bioprocessing Equipment (BPE) Standard was developed to aid in the design and construction of new fluid processing equipment used in the manufacture of biopharmaceuticals, where a defined level of purity and bioburden control is required.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] Within scope also is the design and construction of piping systems for hygienic service.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] Multi-Use metallic, Multi-Use plastic and Single-Use materials of construction and design, are all covered in the scope of the 2022 edition.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] New editions of the ASME BPE Standard may be used beginning with the date of issuance and become effective 6 months after the date of issuance.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] It also provides requirements for single-use systems and components used in the above listed applications.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] This Standard may be used, in whole or in part, for other applications where bioburden risk is a concern.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] This Standard is intended to apply to new fabrication and construction.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] It may be used in other cases with consensus between the system owner/user, engineer, installation contractor, and inspection contractor.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] The ASME BPE is a voluntary consensus standard written by a team of over three hundred balanced subject matter experts.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] These individuals provide their knowledge and experience to drive technology and innovation forward safely and responsibly for the manufacturing of modern biopharmaceuticals.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] ASME controls the development and approval of all content by rigorous policies and procedures, ensuring that a thorough vetting process occurs and that the information published is reliable and trustworthy.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] The Standard (2022 Edition) is split into the following Chapters and Parts.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] The teams that develop each Part function as working teams, to develop, approve and refine content.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] The ASME BPE meets three times a year in person, but offline meetings occur to develop and refine existing content.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] Unless otherwise stated, the sessions are free and open to all, and volunteers are welcome.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] ASME posts the details for all meetings on their website; the link is also below.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] At least as early as April 19, 2011, ASME published a web page which falsely indicated the ASME BPE standard had been adopted by the State of California.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] The statement was based upon California's codification of Section 443, Group L—known as the "L Occupancy"—within Part 1 of the California Building Code.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-bpe] The web page claimed that the "L Occupancy" referenced the ASME BPE standard, but no such reference appears as described.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-burt-l-newkirk-award] Newkirk Award** is an ASME-level award presented to "individuals under the age of 40 who have made a notable contribution to the field of tribology in research or development as evidenced by important tribology publications".
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-burt-l-newkirk-award] Newkirk, who was an expert in the field of tribology.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-leonardo-da-vinci-award] The **American Society of Mechanical Engineers Design and Engineering Division awards** yearly the Leonardo Da Vinci Award to eminent engineers whose design or invention is recognized as an important advance in machine design.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-leonardo-da-vinci-award] The award is named after Leonardo da Vinci.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] ASME Y14.41 was born of the need to utilize Computer-aided design (CAD) data as a manufacturing and/or inspection source.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, solid modeling and CAD were becoming important tools for engineers looking to create and define increasingly complex geometry.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] For example, ergonomic and aerodynamic contoured surfaces were extremely difficult to define on engineering drawings.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] In response to requests from various segments of the industry, a new subcommittee began development of the standard in 1998.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] Since various companies in industries including aerospace, automotive, agricultural, and heavy equipment had already begun utilizing the CAD data for industrial purposes without a standard, several definitions needed to be established as the universal interpretation.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] The standard was written to be independent of any specific CAD software implementation.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] ASME Y14.41 served the basis for the international standard *ISO 16792:2006 Technical product documentation — Digital product definition data practices*.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] Both standards focus on the presentation of Geometric dimensioning and tolerancing (GD&T) together with the geometry of the product.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] The material in the 2012 revision was reorganized to locate all of the information on a topic together in the text.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] This allows the reader to find all of the requirements for a functional area in one location.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] In addition, ASME Y14.41 was revised to incorporate changes based on the needs of industry and to reflect changes made to "ASME Y14.5-2009 Dimensioning and Tolerancing".
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] A definition of data set classifications was developed to describe the combinations of model and drawing graphics sheets that might be required by a customer.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] This material is being included in "ASME Y14.100 Engineering Drawing Practices", as it has broader applicability than is appropriate for ASME Y14.41.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] The standard addresses how to organize and present product definition data using CAD based data.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] These portions cover the practices, requirements, and interpretation of the CAD data when there is no engineering drawing graphic sheet.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] All design requirements are indicated in 3D space and are associated to the model geometry.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] These portions cover cases when both a CAD model and an engineering drawing graphic sheet are both used.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] Design requirements generally are indicated on the drawing graphic sheet.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] Refer to data set classifications in ASME Y14.100.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] The ASME Y14.41 Standard is for any company with engineering, manufacturing, or inspection practices that contain or utilize CAD data.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] If a company designs or creates mock-ups in 3D, then ASME Y14.41 is the standard of choice for universal interpretation and industrial practices.
[src:asme-y14-41/asme-y14-41] If a company employs CAD, computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) or computer-aided inspection (CAI), such as coordinate measuring machine (CMM) inspection, then ASME Y14.41 is the standard of choice for universal interpretation and industrial practices.
